{{Infobox academic | honorific_prefix = | name = Yusufu Bala Usman | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Yusufu Bala Usman | birth_date = 1945 | birth_place = [[Musawa]] | death_date = 2005 | death_place = | death_cause = | region = | nationality = Nigerian | period = | occupation = Historian | title = | boards = <!-- Board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation --> | known_for = | spouse = | children = Halima, Attahiru, Zainab, Mariya, [[Hadiza Bala Usman]], Hassan, Hussain.
| signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | era = | discipline = History | sub_discipline = Nigeiran historiography | denomination = | education = | alma_mater = [[Ahmadu Bello University]] | thesis_title = The Transformation of Katsina, 1796-1903: the overthrow of the Sarauta system and the establishment and evolution of the Emirate | thesis_url = | thesis_year = 1974 | doctoral_advisor = Abdullahi Smith | doctoral_students = | notable_students = [[Garba Nadama]] | main_interests = African history | workplaces = | notable_works = | notable_ideas = | influences = | influenced = | awards = <!--Notable national level awards only--> | website = | footnotes = }} '''Yusufu Bala Usman''' ( 1945 - September 24, 2005) was Nigerian academic, politician and historian who was one of the scholars who shaped Nigerian historiography.<ref>Vaughan, Olufemi. "Falola, Toyin, and Saheed Aderinto. 2010. Nigeria, Nationalism, and Writing History." Africa Today 58.2 (2011): 156+. Academic OneFile. Web. 24 Feb. 2016.</ref> Usman was the founder of the Centre for Democratic Development, Research and Training at Ahmadu Bello University, Zaria.
==Life== Usman was born in [[Musawa]], Katsina State, his father was Durbin of Katsina and brother of [[Usman Nagogo]] and his mother was a daughter of [[Abdullahi Bayero]], former Emir of [[Kano Emirate|Kano]]. He attended Musawa Junior Primary School, Kankia Senior Primary School, Minna Senior Primary School and Government College, Kaduna.<ref>Gwadabe, M.M. "IV Yusufu Bala Usman (1945-2005)." Africa 80.1 (2010): 165+. Academic OneFile. Web. 24 Feb. 2016.</ref> He then went to study at the University Tutorial College and then at [[Lancaster University|University of Lancaster]] where he completed his studies with a degree in History and Political Science. He returned to Nigeria in 1967 to become a teacher at [[Barewa College]], Zaria where he taught until 1971. Usman started his graduate studies in 1970 at Ahmadu Bello University, earning his PhD degree in 1974. He started lecturing at the university as a part-time lecturer before being promoted to full-time.<ref>http://www.gamji.com/article5000/NEWS5240.htm</ref>
During the Nigerian Second Republic, he was briefly the Secretary to the Kaduna State government under the [[People's Redemption Party|PRP]] led [[Balarabe Musa]] administration.
===Academic career=== Usman was a major figure among post colonial historians at Ahmadu Bello University, {{sfn|Mamdani|2012|p=88}} his outlook on African history involves support for the use of oral and linguistic sources along with written and archaeological sources. He felt all sources are subject to bias and that increased scrutiny of oral sources for distortions and colourings was not extended to many written sources by European writers. To him, the historian cannot be divorced from his education and molding as a scholar and the [[historicity]] of the European writers likely influenced some of their writings.{{sfn|Mamdani|2012|p=91}} Some of his reflections on the writing of African history includes a critique of [[Heinrich Barth]], a respected source among Western scholars, Usman thought Barth was too focused on the physical and genetic characteristics of those he was studying{{sfn|Mamdani|2012|p=92}} which he felt was a result of the dominant traditions of nineteenth century European history writing.
