{{self-published|date=June 2011}} [[File:Ibn Wahshiyya's 985 CE translation of the Ancient Egyptian hieroglyph alphabet.jpg|thumb|Ibn Wahshiyya's 985 CE translation of the Ancient Egyptian hieroglyph alphabet]] '''Ibn Wahshiyyah the Nabataean''' ({{lang-ar|ابن وحشية النبطي}}), also known as ʾAbū Bakr ʾAḥmad bin ʿAlī ({{lang-ar|أبو بكر أحمد بن علي}}) (fl. 9th/10th centuries) was an Arab [[alchemist]], [[agriculturalist]], farm [[toxicologist]],<ref name="toxicologist" /> [[Egyptologist]],<ref>El-Daly, Okasha (2005). [https://books.google.com/books?id=rdI96px90kUC&pg=PA169#v=onepage&q&f=false Egyptology : the missing millennium : ancient Egypt in medieval Arabic writings]. London: UCL Press. {{ISBN|9781844720620}}. page 169.</ref> and historian born at Qusayn near [[Kufa]] in [[Iraq]].<ref name=Daly2/> He was one of the first historians to be able to at least partly decipher what was written in the ancient Egyptian hieroglyphs,<ref name=Daly1>Dr. Okasha El Daly (2005), ''Egyptology: The Missing Millennium: Ancient Egypt in Medieval Arabic Writings'', [[University College London|UCL Press]], {{ISBN|1-84472-063-2}} (cf. [http://www.muslimheritage.com/topics/default.cfm?ArticleID=481 Arabic Study of Ancient Egypt] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929083701/http://www.muslimheritage.com/topics/default.cfm?ArticleID=481 |date=2007-09-29 }}, Foundation for Science Technology and Civilisation)</ref> by relating them to the contemporary [[Coptic language]].
==Works== [[Ibn al-Nadim]] (in ''Kitab al-Fihrist'') lists a large number of books on [[Magic (paranormal)|magic]], statues, offerings, agriculture, [[alchemy]], [[physics]] and medicine, that were either written, or translated from older books, by Ibn Wahshiyya.<ref>"First, the books of the Nabatean corpus themselves claim to be translations from "ancient Syriac" (e.g. Filaha 1:5) made by Ibn Wahshiyya" (Hämeen-Anttila, Jaako (2006). [http://www.worldcat.org/title/last-pagans-of-iraq-ibn-wahshiyya-and-his-nabatean-agriculture/oclc/897002278?referer=di&ht=edition The last pagans of Iraq : Ibn Waḥshiyya and his Nabatean agriculture]. Leiden: Brill. {{ISBN|9789004150102}}.)</ref>
His works on alchemy were co-authored with an [[alchemist]] named [[Abu Talib al-Zalyat]]; their works were used by [[Shams al-Din al-Ansari al-Dimashqi|Al-Dimashqi]].<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=E. J. Brill's First Encyclopaedia of Islam, 1913-1936|author=Houtsma, T.|date=1993|volume=4|publisher=E.J. Brill|isbn=9789004097902|url=https://books.google.com.pk/books?id=7CP7fYghBFQC|page=1011|accessdate=10 December 2014}}</ref>
===The ''Nabataean Agriculture''=== {{see also|Muslim Agricultural Revolution}}
{{quote|In agriculture, the ''Filahât al-Nabâtiyyah'' (Nabataean Agriculture) of Ibn Wahshiyya is the most influential of all Muslim works on the subject. Written in the third/ninth century and drawn mostly from Chaldaean and Babylonian sources, the book deals not only with agriculture but also with the esoteric sciences, especially magic and sorcery, and has always been considered to be one of the important books in Arabic on the occult sciences.|[[Seyyed Hossein Nasr|S.H. Nasr]]<ref>"''Natural History''" by [[Seyyed Hossein Nasr|S.H. Nasr]] in ''A History of Muslim Philosophy'', edited and introduced by M.M. Sharif (1966), volume II, p. 1323</ref>}}
Ibn Wahshiyya translated from [[Nabataean Arabic|Nabataean]] the ''Nabataean Agriculture'' (''Kitab al-falaha al-nabatiya''; c. 904), a major treatise on the subject, which was said to be based on ancient [[Babylonia]]n sources.<ref>Jaakko Hämeen-Anttila ''Ideology'' 2002, ''Nabataean Agriculture'' 2006</ref> The book extols Babylonian [[civilization]] against that of the conquering [[Arabs]]. It contains valuable information on agriculture and superstitions, and in particular discusses beliefs attributed to the [[Sabians]] - understood as people who lived [[Pre-Adamite|before Adam]] - that [[Adam]] had parents and that he came from [[History of India|India]]. These ideas were discussed by the Jewish philosophers [[Yehuda Halevi]] and [[Maimonides]], through which they became an influence on the seventeenth century French [[Millenarian]] [[Isaac La Peyrère]].
====Toxicology==== He wrote a toxicology treatise, the ''Book of Poisons'', combining contemporary science, magic and astrology.<ref name="toxicologist">{{cite journal|last=Iovdijová|first=A|author2=Bencko, V|title=Potential risk of exposure to selected xenobiotic residues and their fate in the food chain--part I: classification of xenobiotics|journal=Annals of Agricultural and Environmental Medicine|year=2010|volume=17|issue=2|pages=183–92|pmid=21186759|url=http://www.aaem.pl/pdf/17183.pdf|accessdate=13 June 2011}}</ref>
===Egyptology=== Ibn Wahshiyya was one of the first historians to be able to at least partly decipher what was written in the ancient Egyptian hieroglyphs,<ref name="Daly1"/> by relating them to the contemporary [[Coptic language]] used by [[Copt]]ic priests in his time. An Arabic manuscript of Ibn Wahshiyya's book ''Kitab Shawq al-Mustaham'', a work that discusses a number of ancient alphabets, in which he deciphered a number of Egyptian hieroglyphs, was later read by [[Athanasius Kircher]] in the 17th century, and then translated and published in [[English language|English]] by [[Joseph von Hammer-Purgstall]] in 1806 as ''Ancient Alphabets and Hieroglyphic Characters Explained; with an Account of the Egyptian Priests, their Classes, Initiation, and Sacrifices in the Arabic Language by Ahmad Bin Abubekr Bin Wahishih'', 16 years before [[Jean-François Champollion]]'s complete decipherment of Egyptian hieroglyphs.<ref name=Daly2>Dr. Okasha El Daly, [http://muslimheritage.com/topics/default.cfm?ArticleID=712 Deciphering Egyptian Hieroglyphs in Muslim Heritage], [[Museum of Science and Industry in Manchester]]</ref><ref name="archive">{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/ancientalphabet00conggoog|title=Ancient Alphabets and Hieroglyphic Characters Explained: With an Account of ... : Aḥmad ibn ʻAlī Ibn Waḥshīyah, Ahmed ibn 'Ali ibn al Mukhtar ibn 'Abd al Karim, Joseph Hammer-Purgstall , Pforzheimer Bruce Rogers Collection (Library of Congress) : Free Download &amp; Streaming : Internet Archive|publisher=archive.org|accessdate=10 December 2014}}</ref> This book was known to [[Silvestre de Sacy]], a colleague of Champollion. Dr [[Okasha El Daly]], at [[University College London]]'s Institute of Archaeology, claims that some hieroglyphs had been decoded by Ibn Wahshiyya, eight centuries before Champollion deciphered the [[Rosetta stone]].<ref name=Observer>{{cite news |first=Robin |last=McKie |title=Arab scholar 'cracked Rosetta code' 800 years before the West |url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/uk_news/story/0,6903,1318435,00.html |work=The Observer |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited 2007 |date=2004-10-03 |accessdate=23 May 2007}}</ref> A. K. Eyma critiques this idea and think that "there was no such thing as an Arabic decipherment of hieroglyphs".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.egyptologyforum.org/reviews/Missing1000.html|title=egyptologyforum.org|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>
===Cryptography=== He published several cipher alphabets that were used to encrypt magic formulas.<ref>Whitman, Michael (2010). [https://books.google.com/books?id=L3LtJAxcsmMC&pg=PA351#v=onepage&q&f=false Principles of information security]. London: Course Technology. {{ISBN|1111138214}}. Page 351.</ref>
